fp||cp|2|cs|3|ht|e|at|^b@2Mitch: 

There was one area we mentioned - "misunderstandings" -- 
I would like to do a quick discussion of "walsh style", because even if you don't play it, you will encounter it
If you can, look at deal 2 in the movies
You may remember that N/S missed a 4/4 spade fit

The N hand had 4-3-5-1 shape and after partner opened 1@C, she responded 1@D
North's hand was Kxxx, KJx, K10xxx, x
Walsh style works like this:
Opener starts with 1@C
Responder has a 4 card major and 4 or 5 diamonds
If responder's hand is less than game-forcing, i.e if responder has less than a minimum opening bid, then she bids the major and bypasses the diamond suit

Example 1: Responder has Kxxx, Kxx, Q10xx, xx
Opener bids 1@C
In Standard American, you bid 1@D (bid suits up the line)
But playing Walsh style, you have just 1 bid, in essence, and that is 1@S

Example 2: Jxxx, AQx, KQxxx, x
You have 12 HCP and if opener in first seat has anything resembling a sound minimum opener, you expect to have some shot at game
So you respond 1@D (your 5 card suit). 
Opener will still think you don't have a 4 card major. Right?
Because if you were weak with a 4 card major, you would have bid it

^*BSo opener will not show her own 4 card major unless her hand is unbalanced^*N.|
